{
    "esm": "0.4.0",
    "metadata": {
        "name": "AtmosphericDiffusion",
        "description": "Atmospheric eddy-diffusivity and wind-profile parameterizations from Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Ch. 18, Sec. 18.12. Given a height z above ground, the component computes the mean wind speed u_wind from a power-law profile (Eq. 18.118) and the vertical and horizontal eddy diffusivities K_zz, K_yy that govern turbulent transport of trace species in the planetary boundary layer. K_zz is selected by atmospheric stability from the Monin-Obukhov length L_MO: an unstable four-piece convective profile (Eq. 18.121, Lamb & Duran 1977), a neutral profile (Eq. 18.122, Myrup & Ranzieri 1976), or a stable profile (Eq. 18.125, Businger & Arya 1974). K_yy is 0.1*w_star*z_i under unstable conditions (Eq. 18.128) and equals K_zz otherwise. Three purely-algebraic equations, no time integration. Migrated from AtmosphericDynamics.jl@816cc391 src/atmospheric_diffusion.jl:30 (`AtmosphericDiffusion` @component).",
        "tags": [
            "atmospheric_dynamics",
            "seinfeld-pandis",
            "boundary-layer",
            "eddy-diffusivity",
            "turbulent-transport",
            "wind-profile",
            "observed-only",
            "ch18"
        ],
        "created": "2026-05-17T00:00:00Z",
        "authors": [
            "AtmosphericDynamics.jl contributors",
            "EarthSciModels migration (esm-98a0)"
        ],
        "references": [
            {
                "citation": "Seinfeld, J. H., & Pandis, S. N. (2006). Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics: From Air Pollution to Climate Change, 2nd ed. Wiley. Chapter 18 (Atmospheric Diffusion), Section 18.12, Eqs. 18.118-18.129 — power-law wind profile and the unstable / neutral / stable eddy-diffusivity parameterizations. ISBN 978-0-471-72018-8."
            },
            {
                "citation": "Lamb, R. G., & Duran, D. R. (1977). Eddy diffusivities derived from a numerical model of the convective planetary boundary layer. Il Nuovo Cimento C, 1(1), 1-17. Source of the unstable K_zz profile (Seinfeld & Pandis Eq. 18.121)."
            },
            {
                "citation": "Myrup, L. O., & Ranzieri, A. J. (1976). A consistent scheme for estimating diffusivities to be used in air quality models. California Department of Transportation, Report CA-DOT-TL-7169-3-76-32. Source of the neutral K_zz profile (Seinfeld & Pandis Eq. 18.122)."
            },
            {
                "citation": "Businger, J. A., & Arya, S. P. S. (1974). Height of the mixed layer in the stably stratified planetary boundary layer. Advances in Geophysics, 18A, 73-92. Source of the stable K_zz profile (Seinfeld & Pandis Eq. 18.125)."
            }
        ]
    },
    "models": {
        "AtmosphericDiffusion": {
            "reference": {
                "notes": "source_ref: AtmosphericDynamics.jl@816cc3918e1eef2c2ee6d8fa8dd73c8f13a85a47:src/atmospheric_diffusion.jl:30\n\nUpstream `AtmosphericDiffusion` is an MTK `@component` implementing the atmospheric diffusion parameterizations of Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Ch. 18, Sec. 18.12: the power-law wind profile (Eq. 18.118) and the vertical/horizontal eddy diffusivities K_zz, K_yy across the unstable, neutral and stable boundary-layer regimes (Eqs. 18.119-18.129). It declares 2 `@constants` (kappa, Kzz_zero), 7 `@parameters` (u_r, z_r, p_wind, z_i, L_MO, u_star, f_cor), 4 `@variables` (z, u_wind, K_zz, K_yy) and 3 equations, returning `System(eqs, t)`. The upstream test (test/atmospheric_diffusion_test.jl) compiles it with `mtkcompile(sys; inputs = [z])` and exercises it through a `NonlinearProblem` — there is no time derivative, so the system is purely algebraic.\n\nSystem kind: all 3 equations are explicit algebraic assignments (u_wind ~ ..., K_zz ~ ..., K_yy ~ ...) with no `D(.)` operator. Each output is given directly as a closed-form expression of the inputs — there is no implicit/coupled solve. The migration therefore leaves `system_kind` unset (default 'ode'): the three equations resolve to observed quantities and the compiled system has zero differential states, exactly as for the sibling explicit-algebraic components ideal_gas.esm and scale_height.esm. This is deliberately NOT the blocked `system_kind: nonlinear` class (Mogi, Isorropia) — those need an implicit Newton solve with initial guesses (gap gt-ebuq); AtmosphericDiffusion needs none, which is why docs/migration-tracker.md marks it `blocking_gap: none`.\n\nVariable classification. (1) z: upstream an MTK `@variable` carrying no defining equation; the upstream test pins it as an `mtkcompile` input. It is encoded as `type: parameter` (the ESS analog of an MTK input) — the same convention sibling ideal_gas.esm/scale_height.esm apply to their input @variables. (2) u_wind, K_zz, K_yy: encoded `type: state` (no `default`) — each is the LHS of exactly one purely-algebraic equation, an observed quantity with no time derivative and hence no initial condition (the convention of net_transport / net_chemistry in sibling atmospheric_budget.esm and of H in scale_height.esm). (3) kappa and Kzz_zero: upstream MTK `@constants`; the ESS schema has no `constant` variable type, so both are encoded `type: parameter` — the same treatment scale_height.esm applies to its upstream @constants R, M_air, g. The upstream Greek symbol for the von Karman constant is written here with the ASCII name `kappa`.\n\nabs() wrapping of two fractional-power bases (the one substantive migration adjustment). The upstream convective velocity scale is w_star = u_star*(-z_i/(kappa*L_MO))^(1/3) and the unstable K_zz surface piece carries a factor (1 - 15*z/L_MO)^(1/4). Both fractional powers have bases that are positive whenever the expression is actually *selected* (w_star and the unstable pieces are only reached for L_MO < 0, where -z_i/(kappa*L_MO) > 0 and 1 - 15*z/L_MO = 1 + positive > 0) but go negative in the dead neutral/stable `ifelse` branches (L_MO > 0). The canonical ESS Python runner lowers `ifelse` to `sympy.Piecewise`, which lambdifies to `numpy.select` — and `numpy.select` evaluates every branch eagerly. A negative base under a non-integer power is a complex number, and a single complex branch promotes the whole `numpy.select` result to complex dtype, contaminating even the correctly selected real branch (verified: with the literal upstream base, stable-regime K_zz comes back as `5+0j` instead of `5.0`). Both bases are therefore wrapped in `abs(...)`: in the live regime (L_MO < 0) the bases are already positive so `abs(...)` is the identity and every selected value is bit-identical to the upstream; in the dead branches `abs(...)` keeps the value real and finite so `numpy.select` stays on float64. This is a faithful encoding of the upstream's intent — the upstream relies on `ifelse` never *selecting* the negative-base branches; the .esm additionally ensures those branches never *poison* the eager all-branch evaluation of the ESS runner. No selected output value is changed.\n\nEquation faithfulness. The 3 upstream equations (src/atmospheric_diffusion.jl:135-139) are preserved verbatim: u_wind ~ u_r*(z/z_r)^p_wind (Eq. 18.118); K_zz ~ regime-selected diffusivity (Eqs. 18.119-18.125); K_yy ~ unstable Eq. 18.128 value or K_zz. The upstream Julia locals (w_star, zn, wzi, the four Kzz_unstable pieces, Kzz_unstable / Kzz_neutral / Kzz_stable, L_MO_norm, K_yy_unstable, the u_wind/K_zz/K_yy `_expr` bindings) are not MTK variables — they are plain Julia values holding symbolic expressions, which MTK inlines into the 3 equations when `System(eqs, t)` is built. The .esm mirrors this exactly: the locals are fully inlined into the 3 `equations` entries (so e.g. the w_star sub-tree appears in every Kzz_unstable piece and in K_yy, and the entire K_zz right-hand side reappears inside K_yy), matching what `equations(sys)` shows after the upstream component is built. Subtraction uses the binary `-` op; the unstable piece-2 polynomial 0.021 + 0.408 zn + 1.351 zn^2 - 4.096 zn^3 + 2.56 zn^4 is written as a flat n-ary `+` with the cubic term carrying a negative coefficient. The (4/3), (1/3), (1/4) exponents are encoded as `/` nodes over float literals, mirroring the upstream `(4.0/3.0)`, `(1.0/3.0)`, `(1.0/4.0)`; the integer exponents 2, 3, 4 are integer literals.\n\nUnits. The upstream declares z, z_r, z_i in u\"m\"; u_wind, u_r, u_star in u\"m/s\"; K_zz, K_yy, Kzz_zero in u\"m^2/s\"; f_cor in u\"1/s\"; p_wind and kappa dimensionless (u\"1\"). All are SI-coherent and carried verbatim into the .esm; no unit conversion is applied at migration time. Unit balance (verified): u_wind ~ u_r*(z/z_r)^p_wind is (m/s)*(m/m)^1 = m/s; K_zz ~ w_star*z_i*(dimensionless) and kappa*u_star*z are (m/s)*m = m^2/s; the stable branch kappa*u_star*z/(0.74 + 4.7 z/L)*exp(...) is (m^2/s)/(dimensionless)*(dimensionless) = m^2/s; K_yy ~ 0.1*w_star*z_i = m^2/s. The ifelse branch arguments are dimensionally consistent (m^2/s throughout K_zz; Kzz_zero supplies the m^2/s above-BL fallback).\n\nTolerance rationale (model-level rel=1.0e-6). The system is a closed-form algebraic evaluation — no ODE integration, no implicit solve — so there is no integrator error to bound; rel=1.0e-6 covers float64 round-off in the multiply/divide/exp/power chains and the associativity difference between the migration's left-folded products and sympy's canonical `Mul`/`Add` ordering (a few ULP). This matches the sibling explicit-algebraic components ideal_gas.esm and scale_height.esm (both rel=1.0e-6). The two exact-zero assertions in `neutral_kzz_above_bl_zero` (K_zz and K_yy collapsing to the Kzz_zero fallback) use a per-assertion absolute tolerance abs=1.0e-12, since a relative tolerance cannot gate a true zero.\n\nTest reproduction. The 14 inline tests reproduce every upstream testitem of test/atmospheric_diffusion_test.jl: `Wind Profile (Eq. 18.118)` (z = z_r, z = 50), `Unstable K_zz (Eq. 18.121)` (all four z/z_i pieces at z = 30/300/800/1200), `Neutral K_zz (Eq. 18.122)` (all three branches at z = 50/500/1200), `Stable K_zz (Eq. 18.125)` (z = 50/200), and `Horizontal Diffusivity K_yy` (unstable K_yy = 0.1 w_star z_i, and K_yy = K_zz under stable conditions). `defaults_unstable_z100` additionally exercises all three outputs at once, covering the upstream `AtmosphericDiffusion Structure` and `Qualitative Properties` testitems. Expected values are the exact float64 results of the upstream formulas."
            },
            "tolerance": {
                "rel": 1e-06
            },
            "variables": {
                "z": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 100.0,
                    "description": "Height above ground [m] (Seinfeld & Pandis Ch. 18). The spatial input of the parameterization: the wind speed u_wind and the eddy diffusivities K_zz, K_yy are all evaluated at this height. Upstream `AtmosphericDiffusion` declares z as an MTK `@variable` carrying no defining equation; the upstream test compiles the system with `mtkcompile(sys; inputs = [z])`, pinning z as an externally-supplied input. It is therefore encoded here as `type: parameter` (the ESS analog of an MTK compile-time input), overridable per scenario via `parameter_overrides` and `parameter_sweep` — the same convention sibling AtmosphericDynamics components ideal_gas.esm and scale_height.esm apply to their input @variables T, p. The default 100 m is the canonical probe height used in the upstream test setup (`NonlinearProblem(ssys, Dict(ssys.z => 100.0))`) and the docs examples."
                },
                "u_wind": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m/s",
                    "description": "Mean wind speed at height z [m/s] (Seinfeld & Pandis Eq. 18.118, power-law profile). An observed (algebraic) output — the LHS of exactly one purely-algebraic equation u_wind ~ u_r*(z/z_r)^p_wind, with no time derivative and hence no initial condition. Increases monotonically with height for p_wind > 0."
                },
                "K_zz": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^2/s",
                    "description": "Vertical eddy diffusivity [m^2/s] (Seinfeld & Pandis Eqs. 18.119-18.125). An observed (algebraic) output: the value is selected by the atmospheric stability regime — unstable (Eq. 18.121, Lamb & Duran 1977), neutral (Eq. 18.122, Myrup & Ranzieri 1976), or stable (Eq. 18.125, Businger & Arya 1974) — using the Monin-Obukhov length L_MO. The LHS of one purely-algebraic equation; no time derivative, no initial condition."
                },
                "K_yy": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^2/s",
                    "description": "Horizontal eddy diffusivity [m^2/s] (Seinfeld & Pandis Eqs. 18.126-18.129). An observed (algebraic) output: under unstable conditions K_yy = 0.1*w_star*z_i (Eq. 18.128, roughly constant with height); under neutral and stable conditions K_yy is approximated by K_zz (the common assumption of Sec. 18.12.3). The LHS of one purely-algebraic equation; no time derivative, no initial condition."
                },
                "u_r": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m/s",
                    "default": 5.0,
                    "description": "Reference wind speed [m/s] anchoring the power-law wind profile (Eq. 18.118): u_wind equals u_r at the reference height z_r. Default 5 m/s (upstream @parameter default)."
                },
                "z_r": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 10.0,
                    "description": "Reference height [m] for the power-law wind profile (Eq. 18.118) — the height at which u_wind equals the reference wind speed u_r. Default 10 m (upstream @parameter default), the standard meteorological anemometer height."
                },
                "p_wind": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "1",
                    "default": 0.15,
                    "description": "Power-law exponent (dimensionless) of the wind profile u_wind/u_r = (z/z_r)^p_wind (Eq. 18.118). Default 0.15 (upstream @parameter default), a typical value for near-neutral flow over moderately rough terrain."
                },
                "z_i": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 1000.0,
                    "description": "Mixed-layer (inversion) height [m] — the depth of the convective boundary layer. Sets the normalized height z/z_i that selects the piecewise branches of the unstable and neutral K_zz profiles. Default 1000 m (upstream @parameter default)."
                },
                "L_MO": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": -100.0,
                    "description": "Monin-Obukhov length [m]. Sets the atmospheric stability regime: L_MO < 0 is unstable (convective), L_MO > 0 is stable, and the limit |L_MO| -> infinity is neutral. The regime is selected from the dimensionless ratio L_MO/z_i: |L_MO/z_i| > 10 picks the neutral profile, otherwise L_MO/z_i < 0 picks unstable and L_MO/z_i > 0 picks stable. Default -100 m (upstream @parameter default), an unstable boundary layer."
                },
                "u_star": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m/s",
                    "default": 0.3,
                    "description": "Friction velocity [m/s] — the surface-layer turbulence velocity scale. Appears in the convective velocity scale w_star and in all three K_zz regime formulas. Default 0.3 m/s (upstream @parameter default)."
                },
                "f_cor": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "1/s",
                    "default": 0.0001,
                    "description": "Coriolis parameter [1/s] — the exponential height-decay rate of the stable K_zz profile (Eq. 18.125). Default 1.0e-4 1/s (upstream @parameter default), a mid-latitude value."
                },
                "kappa": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "1",
                    "default": 0.4,
                    "description": "von Karman constant (dimensionless). Default 0.4. Upstream this is an MTK `@constant` (it is excluded from `parameters(sys)`); the ESS schema has no `constant` variable type, so it is encoded here as `type: parameter` — the same treatment sibling scale_height.esm applies to its upstream @constants R, M_air, g. The upstream symbol is the Greek letter kappa; this migration uses the ASCII name `kappa` for it."
                },
                "Kzz_zero": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^2/s",
                    "default": 0.0,
                    "description": "Zero diffusivity [m^2/s], the above-boundary-layer fallback value of the neutral K_zz profile for z/z_i > 1.1 (Eq. 18.122). Default 0.0. Upstream an MTK `@constant` declared with explicit m^2/s units precisely so the neutral-regime `ifelse` branches are unit-consistent; encoded here as `type: parameter` for the same schema reason as kappa."
                }
            },
